# VmMap-Pmap Integration Fixes

The VmMap struct holds a pmap reference but several methods don't update the hardware page tables, and [remove_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#99-112) is a stub that never actually removes entries from the splay tree.

## Audit Findings

### Critical Bugs

| Method | Issue | Severity |
|--------|-------|----------|
| [remove_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#99-112) | Calls `pmap_remove` but **never removes entries from splay tree** — always returns empty Vec | **Critical** |
| [remove_entry_containing](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#89-98) | Doesn't call `pmap_remove` — callers must do it separately | Medium |
| [protect_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#158-166) | `pmap_protect` call is **commented out** with FIXME | Medium |
| [clear](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#61-71) | Replaces tree but doesn't call `pmap_remove` on cleared range | Low |

### Not-bugs (by design)

| Method | Rationale |
|--------|-----------|
| [insert_entry](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#80-88) | Correct: demand paging handles mapping on first fault |
| Fork path | Correct: manipulates pmap directly in [cow_fork_vm](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/proc/fork.rs#109-218) |
| [sys_munmap](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/syscall/memory.rs#105-121) | Works around broken [remove_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#99-112) by calling `pmap_remove` separately |

### Impact Analysis

The broken [remove_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#99-112) means:
- **munmap** calls `pmap_remove` (works around the bug) but the returned Vec is always empty so **VmMapEntries and their VmObjects are never freed** (memory leak, stale VMA metadata in tree)
- **mmap MAP_FIXED** has the same issue — old VMAs remain in the tree alongside new ones

> [!CAUTION]
> [remove_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#99-112) is a no-op stub. This leaks VMAs and their backing VmObjects on every munmap/MAP_FIXED call.

## Proposed Changes

### VmMap core

#### [MODIFY] [mod.rs](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs)

1. **[remove_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#99-112)**: Implement actual entry removal from splay tree. Collect overlapping entries, split boundary entries, remove fully-contained entries. Keep the existing `pmap_remove` call.

2. **[remove_entry_containing](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#89-98)**: Add `pmap_remove` call for the entry's VA range before removing from tree.

3. **[protect_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#158-166)**: Uncomment `pmap_protect` call. The `MapPerm` type already matches what `pmap_protect` expects — both use entry.rs `MapPerm`.

4. **[clear](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#61-71)**: Add `pmap_remove` for the full user VA range before clearing tree, or iterate entries and unmap each.

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
Run `make run-rv64` — the kernel should boot and the shell should get further (beyond the NULL deref at `va=0x78`). The fix to [remove_range](file:///Users/3y/playground/c/freebsd/kernel/src/mm/vm/map/mod.rs#99-112) ensures VMAs are properly managed; it won't directly affect exec demand paging but will fix munmap/brk correctness.

### Manual Verification
After boot, verify the initproc/shell behavior improves. The `[trap] ERROR: fatal fault` at `va=0x78` may still occur if the root cause is elsewhere (dynamic linking, missing syscall), but VmMap operations should now be correct.
